WEBVTT

00:10.140 --> 00:11.402
Pa: We'll find a ride.

00:11.446 --> 00:13.056
I'll stand
in the middle of the road

00:13.100 --> 00:15.015
and force the issue
with my new gun.

00:15.058 --> 00:18.627
♪♪

00:18.670 --> 00:20.977
I told Glenn we were
in a gang

00:21.021 --> 00:23.023
to help with
the getting-the-money thing.

00:23.066 --> 00:24.372
Special Boys.[ Glasses clink ]

00:24.415 --> 00:26.504
Pa: Donny -- he's out.

00:26.548 --> 00:28.115
Official:
Petitioning for passport?

00:28.158 --> 00:29.246
Donny: I am.

00:29.290 --> 00:30.682
Purpose?

00:30.726 --> 00:32.467
Visit an old friend.

00:32.510 --> 00:34.164
Glenn's home,
Ranger.

00:34.208 --> 00:35.252
He brought me
something home.

00:35.296 --> 00:36.384
From his trip?

00:36.427 --> 00:38.734
Yeah.

00:38.777 --> 00:40.518
Paul Brown?

00:40.562 --> 00:42.651
-Yeah.
-You are a person of interest

00:42.694 --> 00:45.654
in the murder
of Theresa Sincere Williams.

00:45.697 --> 00:48.352
Are you gonna stop talking to
Walker Texas Ranger?

00:48.396 --> 00:51.399
Are we gonna bring your mother
and father's bodies home

00:51.442 --> 00:55.794
from Mexico so we can bury them
properly, Paul, for the funeral?

00:55.838 --> 00:57.057
We are.

00:57.100 --> 00:58.710
Let's get
your parents home.

00:58.754 --> 01:03.585
The lawful and healthful
process of retrieval.

01:03.628 --> 01:06.675
How many kids did
the fire-trainee guy have?

01:06.718 --> 01:09.243
The guy who burned
holding your hose?

01:09.286 --> 01:11.114
James: 11.

01:11.158 --> 01:12.811
My loving mother and father

01:12.855 --> 01:14.378
will pass
in a matter of days.

01:14.422 --> 01:18.469
It's a "Your Parents
Are Dead Now" vibration thing.

01:18.513 --> 01:21.733
If you don't return
what you took from them -- me --

01:21.777 --> 01:24.388
when it vibrates,
I'm going to kill you.

01:24.432 --> 01:27.217
[ Vibrating ]

01:27.261 --> 01:37.140
♪♪

01:41.188 --> 01:44.060
[ Water lapping ]

01:53.374 --> 01:56.725
Paul: The wire transfer takes
three days, I found out.

01:56.768 --> 01:58.814
Besides that, I'm ready.

01:58.857 --> 02:01.338
How much?

02:01.382 --> 02:03.862
Almost all.

02:06.213 --> 02:07.779
So.

02:09.477 --> 02:11.653
So I don't know.

02:14.960 --> 02:17.049
It's not really
his money.

02:17.093 --> 02:19.139
It's the church's money.

02:19.182 --> 02:22.664
And church --
that's just people.

02:22.707 --> 02:24.666
It's going back,
though.

02:24.709 --> 02:27.408
After you take it,
you're going to put it back.

02:31.760 --> 02:34.023
[ Sighs ]

02:37.026 --> 02:39.028
Hey!
We'll miss this bus!

02:39.071 --> 02:40.856
Theresa: I'm coming!

02:51.606 --> 02:52.563
[ Metal clangs ]

02:52.607 --> 02:54.696
[ Chuckles ]

02:56.828 --> 02:59.135
My Houdini cuffs
didn't show.

02:59.179 --> 03:01.616
When did you
order them?

03:01.659 --> 03:03.313
Yesterday.

03:03.357 --> 03:06.534
Well, mail always takes,
like, three days.

03:06.577 --> 03:09.624
Grab your stuff.
Let's go.

03:17.022 --> 03:18.720
How long
until we're there?

03:18.763 --> 03:20.548
Paul:
Uh, an hour to LaGrange,

03:20.591 --> 03:23.115
then an hour wait
for the next bus,

03:23.159 --> 03:25.553
and then two hours more
to Houston.

03:25.596 --> 03:27.555
"Star Search," baby.

03:27.598 --> 03:29.252
Well,
this is the tryouts.

03:29.296 --> 03:30.819
If we try out well,

03:30.862 --> 03:33.822
then we go to the real show
later in New York,

03:33.865 --> 03:36.520
where all
the tryout winners go.

03:40.611 --> 03:41.699
Paul?

03:41.743 --> 03:43.266
Yeah?

03:43.310 --> 03:45.268
I've thought about it.

03:45.312 --> 03:48.793
I wish --
You know what I wish?

03:48.837 --> 03:50.969
What do you wish?

03:51.013 --> 03:54.408
I wish I hadn't heard you
when I was hunkered.

03:54.451 --> 03:56.279
Yeah.

03:56.323 --> 03:58.325
I wish I was magic
for real.

03:58.368 --> 04:01.763
Mm. Magic for real
would be cool.

04:01.806 --> 04:05.114
If I was magic for real,
I'd unhear you.

04:05.157 --> 04:08.726
Yeah.
Unhearing would be cool.

04:08.770 --> 04:11.816
But, yeah.

04:11.860 --> 04:15.820
Yeah.

04:17.953 --> 04:20.825
I wish
I hadn't heard you.

04:22.218 --> 04:24.438
Yeah.

04:27.354 --> 04:28.964
I have to tell him.

04:29.007 --> 04:34.361
My dad's a deacon, and, well,
it ain't right, as they say.

04:34.404 --> 04:36.711
It's all the money
in the church.

04:36.754 --> 04:40.236
It ain't right,
as they say.

04:41.803 --> 04:43.152
Are you mad?

04:43.195 --> 04:44.980
No.

04:45.023 --> 04:46.634
No way.

04:46.677 --> 04:49.245
You're right.

04:49.289 --> 04:51.943
It ain't right.

04:53.293 --> 04:54.946
Now I'm happy again.

04:54.990 --> 04:57.253
[ Chuckles ]
Good.

04:57.297 --> 05:00.300
You're true blue.

05:00.343 --> 05:03.999
And that's the best color
out of all colors.

05:04.042 --> 05:08.220
So...cool.

05:08.264 --> 05:10.353
[ Engine rumbling ]

05:13.443 --> 05:15.489
[ Birds chirping ]

05:36.597 --> 05:39.208
[ Hector speaking Spanish]

05:39.251 --> 05:40.252
[ Beep]

05:40.296 --> 05:42.820
[ Sighs ]

05:42.864 --> 05:45.388
James:
Is your dad a fast driver?

05:45.432 --> 05:47.695
Paul:
Pa's normal. Driver.

05:47.738 --> 05:50.045
Ma drives fast as shit.

05:50.088 --> 05:53.657
They could get to Half Acre
in 10 hours if Ma drives.

05:56.486 --> 06:01.535
Hector called Valerie yesterday,
said he had a cool plan.

06:01.578 --> 06:04.320
Well, if his cool plan
was still cool,

06:04.364 --> 06:06.931
probably he'd be
picking up my calls.

06:16.071 --> 06:18.856
I put out
the Uncle Dave fire.

06:18.900 --> 06:20.945
Good.

06:34.481 --> 06:36.439
Do you talk about these things
in terms of fires

06:36.483 --> 06:37.919
just to
fuck with my head?

06:37.962 --> 06:40.008
'Cause you know I have
a fire past that --

06:40.051 --> 06:42.402
Oh, shit, man.
I'm so sorry.

06:50.322 --> 06:53.021
I'm so sorry, man.
I am so sorry.

06:53.064 --> 06:56.285
I totally forgot.
Whoa.

06:56.328 --> 07:00.289
I would never bring that up in
that kind of way, never, ever.

07:00.332 --> 07:03.901
That must be so painful,
yeah, down in there.

07:03.945 --> 07:05.425
Okay, just --
Down in there.

07:05.468 --> 07:06.904
Just --
It's whatever.

07:06.948 --> 07:10.517
How do you do that,
anyway?

07:10.560 --> 07:11.996
Do what?

07:12.040 --> 07:13.302
What do you mean,
"what"?

07:13.345 --> 07:15.609
Fucking disappearing
and reappearing.

07:15.652 --> 07:17.872
Unh-unh.
That's a magic no-no.

07:17.915 --> 07:22.093
You kind of owe me one
for the -- for the murder thing.

07:22.137 --> 07:26.315
Yeah, well...

07:26.358 --> 07:28.752
Shoot.

07:28.796 --> 07:31.451
It's kind of a big deal,
betraying magic.

07:31.494 --> 07:33.148
Yeah.

07:33.191 --> 07:38.370
Being investigated for murder is
that, Paul, big-deal-wise.

07:38.414 --> 07:40.503
Yeah.

07:40.547 --> 07:42.244
Yeah.

07:42.287 --> 07:45.465
Well...

07:45.508 --> 07:47.858
alright.

07:47.902 --> 07:50.513
I hunker.

07:50.557 --> 07:51.514
You what?

07:51.558 --> 07:53.690
Hunker down.

07:53.734 --> 07:54.996
It's kind of my thing.

07:55.039 --> 07:56.998
Like,
I'm the best in the world.

07:57.041 --> 07:58.347
At hunkering?

07:58.390 --> 08:00.349
Yeah. Yeah, through training,
through --

08:00.392 --> 08:01.829
through
hunkering training.

08:01.872 --> 08:03.352
You have to start
when you're young and --

08:03.395 --> 08:05.746
Well,
how do you move to --I scurry.

08:05.789 --> 08:07.008
You what?

08:07.051 --> 08:10.490
Scurry...
while I'm hunkered.

08:15.146 --> 08:16.757
[ Sighs heavily ]

08:16.800 --> 08:18.846
[ Insects chirping ]

08:36.690 --> 08:39.083
Yeah, anyway,
I was saying --

08:39.127 --> 08:42.870
Hey,
sorry about the fire talk.

08:42.913 --> 08:48.658
But, fuck, I think I got us into
more trouble with Dave.

08:48.702 --> 08:51.139
In -- In putting out
the Uncle Dave fire,

08:51.182 --> 08:55.404
I-I think maybe I started
an even bigger fire.

08:55.447 --> 08:57.493
How?

08:57.537 --> 08:59.364
A funeral.

08:59.408 --> 09:00.844
He wants a funeral.

09:00.888 --> 09:03.673
Yeah.
A creepy undertaker came.

09:03.717 --> 09:09.461
Yeah. Probably for that,
we have to have bodies.

09:09.505 --> 09:13.988
Uh...
and we don't, so...

09:14.031 --> 09:16.556
Yeah.

09:16.599 --> 09:17.905
Fire.

09:17.948 --> 09:20.255
Sorry.

09:20.298 --> 09:23.475
I'm still here.

09:23.519 --> 09:24.825
I'm just low.

09:24.868 --> 09:28.132
How are we gonna
get two bodies?

09:28.176 --> 09:32.180
I'm coming back there
so we can put a plan together

09:32.223 --> 09:33.921
for keeping this on track

09:33.964 --> 09:36.924
because if we don't have
these bodies in three days,

09:36.967 --> 09:41.058
that'll start to unravel
this whole dark caper.

09:44.801 --> 09:48.065
Alright. Bodies.
How? Go.

09:50.024 --> 09:51.547
What do you mean,
"go"?

09:51.591 --> 09:53.157
We're brainstorming.
Go.

09:53.201 --> 09:55.595
You fucking go.
I don't know how to get bodies.

09:55.638 --> 09:58.859
Yeah, well,
me either, man.

10:00.251 --> 10:02.950
[ Scoffs ]

10:02.993 --> 10:04.821
Can't we just say
that we cremated them

10:04.865 --> 10:07.258
and then just sweep up some dust
or something?

10:07.302 --> 10:10.000
No.
My mom's down on cremation.

10:10.044 --> 10:12.046
You want to hear
a sad story?

10:12.089 --> 10:14.744
No. I want $2 million to pay for
11 girl tuitions.

10:14.788 --> 10:16.137
That's around the corner.

10:16.180 --> 10:20.097
Meanwhile, yeah,
Dave and my mom --

10:20.141 --> 10:23.623
they met in a foster home
when they were 11.

10:23.666 --> 10:25.929
They're not a real
brother and sister.

10:25.973 --> 10:27.322
They just
call each other that

10:27.365 --> 10:31.021
'cause they wanted family
real bad.

10:31.065 --> 10:33.720
And they made one
with each other.

10:33.763 --> 10:35.156
They know everything
about each other,

10:35.199 --> 10:37.419
like a brother
and sister.

10:37.462 --> 10:39.203
They're five-ever.

10:39.247 --> 10:41.162
So,
if we just swept up dust,

10:41.205 --> 10:43.555
he would know it was just dust
and not his sister

10:43.599 --> 10:46.646
'cause he knows
she wants to be buried

10:46.689 --> 10:49.170
with, uh,
an orphan hairbrush.

10:49.213 --> 10:51.781
So we need bodies.

10:51.825 --> 10:53.914
Yeah.

10:56.046 --> 10:57.874
Go.

10:57.918 --> 10:59.659
You haven't gone yet.

10:59.702 --> 11:03.184
Maybe we can rent old people and
tell them to hold their breath.

11:03.227 --> 11:04.446
Go.

11:04.489 --> 11:05.708
That's fucking ridiculous.

11:05.752 --> 11:07.275
Yeah. I went, though.
Go.

11:07.318 --> 11:09.407
Okay, then I'll just
say something stupid, too,

11:09.451 --> 11:10.800
and then it'll be
your turn again.

11:10.844 --> 11:12.367
Well, then maybe I'll say
something stupid.

11:12.410 --> 11:13.890
Well, then we're not going to
fucking get away with it,

11:13.934 --> 11:15.239
Paul, okay?

11:15.283 --> 11:16.893
At some point, we have to
come up with a good,

11:16.937 --> 11:18.678
practical way to --
Yeah.

11:18.721 --> 11:20.201
We can't just
take stupid turns.

11:20.244 --> 11:21.550
Yeah,
you're so right, man.

11:21.593 --> 11:22.725
Okay. Thanks.
Let's just --

11:22.769 --> 11:25.728
Right. Good ideas.
Yeah.

11:25.772 --> 11:29.036
New Leaf:
Paul Allen Brown?

11:29.079 --> 11:31.038
Paul Allen Brown.

11:31.081 --> 11:33.693
Paul Brown,
motherfucker.

11:38.654 --> 11:42.397
♪♪

11:42.440 --> 11:46.401
♪ One day you'll
buy a ride on a comet ♪

11:46.444 --> 11:49.752
♪ And you'll ride
into the sunset ♪

11:49.796 --> 11:52.929
♪ Of a planet
that's beyond it ♪

11:52.973 --> 11:57.325
♪ Beyond the wall

11:57.368 --> 11:59.283
♪ Of all there is

11:59.327 --> 12:01.677
♪♪

12:01.721 --> 12:05.376
♪ And you will stash it
in your pocket ♪

12:05.420 --> 12:08.379
♪ And you'll take it
to Manhattan ♪

12:08.423 --> 12:12.166
♪ Where your grandma's 10,
and you are 10 ♪

12:12.209 --> 12:15.691
♪ You're not a family man,
you're best ♪

12:15.735 --> 12:17.693
♪ Friends

12:17.737 --> 12:21.653
♪ And you will
hold it together ♪

12:21.697 --> 12:24.744
♪ Under the oldest
running water ♪

12:24.787 --> 12:27.790
♪ Of the river of each other

12:27.834 --> 12:32.708
♪ With the power of the future

12:32.752 --> 12:35.406
♪♪

12:35.450 --> 12:39.019
♪ One day you'll ride
into the dawning ♪

12:39.062 --> 12:42.196
♪ Of the morning
of the dreaming ♪

12:42.239 --> 12:45.590
♪ And the sundown
of the nearing ♪

12:45.634 --> 12:49.551
♪ The evening of

12:49.594 --> 12:52.554
♪ Of the living

13:02.738 --> 13:05.088
[ Thunder rumbles ]

13:05.132 --> 13:08.962
Dave: A man can't learn
very much in a toll booth.

13:09.005 --> 13:12.443
Jack S, really.

13:12.487 --> 13:15.577
Total Jack S.

13:18.536 --> 13:20.582
Hey, you know what's cool?

13:20.625 --> 13:24.020
Byron wants to be buried
with a comb.

13:24.064 --> 13:25.456
[ Children screaming ]

13:25.500 --> 13:28.808
Held onto that mother f'er
for 15 rounds,

13:28.851 --> 13:31.027
all the way to the bell.

13:31.071 --> 13:35.031
Kept it, even though
he's bald as S.

13:35.075 --> 13:38.556
Ah, Lillian.

13:38.600 --> 13:40.994
We're gonna bury her
with a brush,

13:41.037 --> 13:45.607
Byron with his own memento
of life's struggle.

13:45.650 --> 13:48.131
Brush and comb.

13:48.175 --> 13:51.918
Awfully pretty.

13:51.961 --> 13:55.835
And I'll place these items
softly on their bodies

13:55.878 --> 14:02.754
in three days and let them down
into the earth like rain.

14:04.321 --> 14:06.019
It went off,
So-Called.

14:06.062 --> 14:08.630
New Leaf --It buzzed, motherfucker.

14:08.673 --> 14:10.937
New Leaf,
you look fucked up.

14:10.980 --> 14:12.852
Come on, man.

14:12.895 --> 14:14.331
Come on.
You're fucked up.

14:14.375 --> 14:15.855
So what?

14:15.898 --> 14:17.682
I once knew you
as Paul Brown,

14:17.726 --> 14:19.336
and then I told you
I was gonna kill you.

14:19.380 --> 14:21.164
And then you told me
you were someone else.

14:21.208 --> 14:23.645
What?
You were once Paul Brown?

14:23.688 --> 14:26.517
Alright.
Once is cool.

14:26.561 --> 14:28.215
One is enough for me,
motherfucker,

14:28.258 --> 14:31.044
for Kevin
and Denise Connelly.

14:31.087 --> 14:33.611
Look here,
Once Paul Allen Brown,

14:33.655 --> 14:35.787
taker of my mother
and father's money,

14:35.831 --> 14:38.529
you're living in
your last moment.

14:39.574 --> 14:41.881
I'm Paul Brown.

14:41.924 --> 14:43.317
Hey. Over here.

14:43.360 --> 14:45.101
I'm Paul Brown.

14:45.145 --> 14:48.583
[ Gunshots ]

14:48.626 --> 14:49.671
Fuck!

14:49.714 --> 14:51.629
Jesus Christ.

14:51.673 --> 14:53.153
Come closer!

14:53.196 --> 14:56.896
No! What do you think,
I'm fucking stupid?

15:00.682 --> 15:03.598
[ Sighs ]

15:03.641 --> 15:05.861
[ Grunts,
exhales heavily ]

15:05.905 --> 15:08.995
[ Sighs ]

15:29.841 --> 15:31.365
[ Sniffles ]

15:35.282 --> 15:36.761
Hey.

15:36.805 --> 15:39.025
What?

15:40.983 --> 15:42.767
I'm sorry.

15:42.811 --> 15:45.857
About what?

15:45.901 --> 15:47.642
What do you mean,
about what?

15:47.685 --> 15:49.470
About your mom and dad.

15:51.428 --> 15:53.778
Is that guy
still out there?

15:53.822 --> 15:57.043
I can't see
'cause of tears.

15:57.086 --> 15:59.480
Yeah.

15:59.523 --> 16:01.003
[ Sighs ]

16:02.048 --> 16:03.484
Stop doing that,
man.

16:03.527 --> 16:05.660
He's not a bad guy.

16:05.703 --> 16:07.618
How did he
just appear?

16:07.662 --> 16:10.404
He's magic.

16:12.797 --> 16:14.103
Cool.

16:14.147 --> 16:16.018
I mean,
he's not really magic.

16:16.062 --> 16:17.933
He's a magician.

16:17.977 --> 16:20.414
He's pretty good.

16:20.457 --> 16:22.633
Yeah.

16:22.677 --> 16:24.896
He's pretty good at
that one thing, anyway.

16:24.940 --> 16:26.289
The best in the world!

16:26.333 --> 16:29.075
He's the best in the world
at that one.

16:29.118 --> 16:31.816
Cool.

16:31.860 --> 16:34.297
He didn't take your parents'
money, New Leaf.

16:34.341 --> 16:36.430
His parents did.

16:36.473 --> 16:39.041
It's the truth,
and we're trying to get it back.

16:39.085 --> 16:43.524
It's too late.
For me.

16:43.567 --> 16:46.570
They're in the by-and-by.

16:46.614 --> 16:50.052
They're in the sky,
man, flying.

16:50.096 --> 16:53.186
[ Breathes raggedly ]

16:53.229 --> 16:56.276
They're so gone,
So-Called.

16:58.278 --> 16:59.975
It's not So-Called,
New Leaf.

17:00.019 --> 17:01.977
My name's James Schaeler.

17:02.021 --> 17:05.067
It's not New Leaf,
James.

17:07.113 --> 17:09.071
I'm a fucking scumbag.

17:09.115 --> 17:11.987
I'm gonna change my name
to that.

17:12.031 --> 17:13.771
That's not -- That --

17:13.815 --> 17:18.341
That would stop you
from...opportunities.

17:18.385 --> 17:20.561
What opportunities?

17:20.604 --> 17:22.867
In future life.

17:22.911 --> 17:26.436
There is no future life
for us.

17:26.480 --> 17:28.786
♪♪

17:28.830 --> 17:30.658
Us what?

17:30.701 --> 17:34.140
Us what, New Leaf?

17:34.183 --> 17:37.839
For all us Supergiants,
James.

17:37.882 --> 17:40.668
The largest star,

17:40.711 --> 17:45.934
huge amounts of energy,
violence...

17:45.977 --> 17:52.854
greater than the sun...
short-lived...massive...

17:52.897 --> 17:56.945
burning,
until it all just explodes.

17:56.988 --> 18:03.169
Supergiants,
destined to end life violently.

18:05.258 --> 18:07.260
Isn't your dad
a spaceman?

18:10.219 --> 18:12.482
Yeah.

18:12.526 --> 18:16.965
He didn't teach you
about supergiants?

18:17.008 --> 18:20.229
No. We didn't spend much time
together.

18:20.273 --> 18:23.276
My dad was a plumber.

18:23.319 --> 18:25.408
We spent a lot of time
together.

18:25.452 --> 18:27.628
And he taught me
about that.

18:27.671 --> 18:29.238
Good dad.

18:29.282 --> 18:31.327
Yeah.

18:31.371 --> 18:33.416
Bad kid.

18:33.460 --> 18:36.767
I was a bad kid, too.

18:36.811 --> 18:39.248
Where is he?

